# HomeCore Appliance {{VERSION}} ({{PLATFORM}})

Core kernel + every official plugin in a single tarball. Statically-linked
musl binaries — no glibc, no OpenSSL, no system dependencies.

## Layout

    homecore/
    ├── bin/homecore                  # the daemon
    ├── config/
    │   ├── homecore.toml.example
    │   └── profiles/
    ├── ui/dist/                      # Leptos Web UI WASM bundle
    ├── scripts/
    │   └── service-templates/        # systemd unit template
    └── plugins/
        ├── hc-hue/{bin,config}
        ├── hc-yolink/{bin,config}
        ├── hc-lutron/{bin,config}
        └── … all bundled plugins

## First run

    cp config/homecore.toml.example config/homecore.toml
    $EDITOR config/homecore.toml
    ./bin/homecore --config config/homecore.toml

The REST API listens on `:8080`. The embedded MQTT broker binds to
`127.0.0.1:1883` by default — read the "Security model" section of the
docs before exposing it on the LAN.

## Enabling plugins

The plugin binaries are present on disk, but only the plugins explicitly
listed in `config/homecore.toml` get spawned. Add a `[[plugins]]` block
per device integration you actually want — see
`config/homecore.toml.example` for the format and the plugin list
available in this archive. Each plugin's `config/config.toml.example`
documents its specific fields.

## Verifying this archive

    sha256sum -c homecore-appliance-{{VERSION}}-{{PLATFORM}}.tar.gz.sha256

If verification fails, do not extract.

## systemd

`scripts/service-templates/homecore.service` is a systemd unit template.
Edit the paths inside to match your install location, then:

    sudo cp scripts/service-templates/homecore.service /etc/systemd/system/
    sudo systemctl daemon-reload
    sudo systemctl enable --now homecore.service
    sudo journalctl -u homecore.service -f

